<paragraph id="3D7B160BDE61FF94D712FA94FBAF9BD3" blockId="4.[194,1119,1339,1466]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Femur Patella Tibia Metatarsus I 1(0)p 1d 2p 1r II – 1d 1d 1p 1r III – 1d 1d 1p 1r 1d 1p 1r IV – 1d 2d 1p 1d 1p</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D7B160BDE61FF94D6E4FA74FB99983F" blockId="4.[166,1225,1499,1846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">
Epigyne as in 
<figureCitation id="A5FF0A8EDE61FF94D7BFFA74FDC99B9F" box="[384,547,1499,1526]" captionStart="Figs 40–51" captionStartId="9.[174,213,1747,1769]" captionTargetBox="[189,1210,673,1697]" captionTargetId="figure-133@9.[189,1210,673,1697]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 40–51. Epigynes of Nediphya hippai sp. n. (40–41, 46, 49), N. padillai sp. n. (42), N. lehtineni (43, 50–51), N. lyleae sp. n. (44–45, 48) and Diphya macrophthalma (47). Scale = 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Cd copulatory ducts, Er elongate anterior receptacles, Mp median plate, Re round proper receptacles, Rr round anterior receptacles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454201" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454201/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">figs 43, 50–51</figureCitation>
, with subtriangular median plate slightly wider than long; copulatory ducts almost parallel, separated by less than one diameter; 2 pairs of receptacles visible through integument; vulva with round proper receptacles (
<emphasis id="0FB0CA19DE61FF94D5B3F9B3FC43985C" box="[908,937,1564,1589]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Re</emphasis>
) and 2 weakly sclertozied pairs of anterior receptacles, one pair rounded (
<emphasis id="0FB0CA19DE61FF94D4F7F993FD0E983C" box="[712,740,1596,1621]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Rr</emphasis>
) and the other pair elongated (
<emphasis id="0FB0CA19DE61FF94D277F993FB89983C" box="[1096,1123,1596,1621]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Er</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D7B160BDE61FF94D6E4F9F4FCD598FF" blockId="4.[166,1225,1499,1846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">
Note. In 
<taxonomicName id="FAC46D88DE61FF94D76AF9F3FE11981F" box="[341,507,1627,1654]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Nanometa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="0FB0CA19DE61FF94D76AF9F3FE3A981C" box="[341,464,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Nanometa</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="59556BFADE61FF94D435F9F4FC4F981F" author="Alvarez-Padilla, F. &amp; Hormiga, G." box="[522,933,1627,1654]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207" pagination="713 - 879" refId="ref5540" refString="Alvarez-Padilla, F., Hormiga, G. 2011. Morphological and phylogenetic atlas of the orb-weaving spider family Tetragnathidae (Araneae: Araneoidea). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 62, 713 - 879." type="journal article" year="2011">Álvarez-Padilla &amp; Hormiga (2011)</bibRefCitation>
interpreted the anterior pairs of receptacles as being part of the copulatory ducts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D7B160BDE61FF94D6E4F934FDA098BF" blockId="4.[166,1225,1499,1846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">
Distribution. The new species is known only from the 
<typeStatus id="E27FA8A9DE61FF94D549F934FC4298DF" box="[886,936,1691,1718]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">type</typeStatus>
locality where 
<taxonomicName id="FAC46D88DE61FF94D266F934FF1A98BC" authority="Marusik &amp; Omelko, 2017" authorityName="Marusik &amp; Omelko" authorityYear="2017" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Nediphya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippai" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="0FB0CA19DE61FF94D266F934FF1A98BC" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Nediphya hippai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="14837762DE61FF94D6C8F914FEDF98BF" box="[247,309,1723,1750]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also known to occur.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D7B160BDE61FF94D6E4F974FDCF995F" blockId="4.[166,1225,1499,1846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">
Etymology. The species name is a patronym in honour of our senior colleague Pekka Lehtinen (Turku, 
<collectingCountry id="45D3569BDE61FF94D741F954FE31997F" box="[382,475,1787,1814]" name="Finland" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Finland</collectingCountry>
) who collected the 
<typeStatus id="E27FA8A9DE61FF94D4F5F954FCDB997F" box="[714,817,1787,1814]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">holotype</typeStatus>
as well as specimens of the other three species of 
<taxonomicName id="FAC46D88DE61FF94D75FF8B4FE3A995C" authority="Marusik &amp; Omelko, 2017" authorityName="Marusik &amp; Omelko" authorityYear="2017" box="[352,464,1819,1845]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Nediphya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="0FB0CA19DE61FF94D75FF8B4FE3A995C" box="[352,464,1819,1845]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="207">Nediphya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="14837762DE61FF94D7E8F8B4FDCF995F" box="[471,549,1819,1846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="207" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
